                    <h3 style="padding:0;width:100%;font-family:Georgia, 'Times New Roman', Times, serif;font-weight:700;font-size:16px;color:#93888F;line-height:23.1px;text-align: left;margin:0;text-transform:uppercase">telecoms</h3>
                </div>
                <div style="width:100%;background-color: transparent">
                    <h3 style="width:100%;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left">Kenya&#8217;s telecoms regulator proposes to fine telcos over poor service quality</h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">


                        <a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
                             <img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2026/05/images-11.jpg" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
                         <figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image Source: Tenor</figcaption>
                    </figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0">Kenya&#8217;s Communications Authority (CA), the country&#8217;s telecoms regulator, is done issuing warnings. For the first time, the regulator is <a>proposing financial penalties</a> and business sanctions against mobile operators that fail to meet minimum network quality standards, marking a significant shift from a compliance regime that has historically had no real teeth.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>Poor standards warranted the hard stance.</strong> In the latest quality of service (QoS) assessment for the year ended June 2025, Telkom Kenya scored 52.76%, down from 67.6% the previous year, well below the current minimum threshold of 80%. Airtel Kenya scored 81.14%, technically above the floor but still declining. Safaricom came closest to the proposed new standard of 90%, posting 89.72%, but still fell short. Under the new rules, none of them would have been fully compliant.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0">What makes this proposal structurally different is not just the higher bar. It is where penalties will be applied. The regulator is introducing county-level enforcement, meaning an operator can face sanctions in specific regions even if its national average looks acceptable. That directly targets the urban-rural quality gap that has persisted for years, where consumers outside Nairobi and major towns, <a>such as Pokot and Turkana</a>, routinely get a worse product for the same price.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>Zoom out: </strong>The telcos will likely push back, and their arguments are not entirely without merit. Rural infrastructure is expensive to build, prone to vandalism, and vulnerable to power disruptions. The returns rarely justify the investment on commercial terms alone. But that is precisely the point. A regulator that could only issue warnings had no leverage to change that incentive. One that can impose quarterly fines, per county, does.</p>
</div>
